# Git Commit Conventions

This project uses commit messages following the ZeroMQ C4 standard with type prefixes.

## Format

```
<type>: <short description>

- Detail 1
- Detail 2
```

## Types

| Type | Description |
|------|-------------|
| `feat:` | New feature or functionality |
| `fix:` | Bug fix |
| `refactor:` | Code restructuring without changing behavior |
| `docs:` | Documentation changes |
| `chore:` | Maintenance, dependencies, tooling |
| `style:` | Formatting, whitespace (no code change) |

## Examples

```
feat: migrate zsh to modules_v2 with shells tag

- Create modules_v2/common/shell/zsh with tag-based enablement
- Use mkDotfilesSymlink for live-editable config
- Apply zsh config to all enabled hostUsers automatically
- Remove old modules/common/shell/zsh
- Enable "shells" tag in nix-goldstar user config
```

```
refactor: split desktop utils into individual modules

- Create separate modules under modules_v2/common/desktop/
  - launcher.nix (rofi)
  - audio.nix (pamixer, pavucontrol)
  - notifications.nix (dunst)
- All share "desktop-utils" tag for unified enablement
```

```
chore: move boot settings to hardware-configuration.nix

- Move boot.kernelPackages to hardware-configuration.nix
- Move boot.loader settings to hardware-configuration.nix
- Keep host default.nix focused on module enablement
```

## Guidelines

- First line: type + concise description (imperative mood)
- Blank line after first line
- Body: bullet points with specific changes
- Keep first line under 72 characters
- Be specific about what was added/removed/changed
